Synthesis of 4-Deoxyaklanonic  acid and  Its  Microbial  Conversion into Anthracyclinones**  Very little is known about the intermediates in the biosyn-  thesis  of  polyketides  on  the  way  from  the  hypothetical  enyzme-bound  open-chain  polyketo  precursor  to  the  cy-  clized  final  products.[']  A  notable  exception  to  this  is  aklanonic acid 1, a partially cyclized anthracycline precursor  which is produced  by mutants of Streptomyces gal2aeu.s and  Slreptomyces peucetius.I2I It was isolated  as a block mutant  product and is considered to be the most important interme-  diate in  anthracycline  biosynthesi~.[~I The incorporation of  isotopically labeled alkanonic acid 1 into a variety of anthra-  cyclines has  demonstrated that  aklanonic acid  is  really  an  intermediate  and not merely a shunt p r o d ~ c t . We  report  here  the  synthesis  and  the  biotransformation  of  the  unnatural  4-deoxyak-  lanonic acid 2 to anthracyclinones  of the aklavinone  type.  The synthesis of 2 starts from the well-known homophtha-  late  monoester  3,15] which  is  treated  with  an excess of  the  dilithium salt of  tert-butylacetoacetate  dianion  (Scheme 1).  The mutant  strain  used  (S727) was obtained  by  treating  Streptomyces gaiilaeus (cinerubin producer) with the potent  mutagen  N-methyl-N'-nitro-N'-nitrosoguanidine (MNNG)  ( 2  mgmL-'  at pH  9.0).  The mutant  strain  S727  does  not  enrich anthracyclines or anthracyclinones and was first used  to convert aklanonic acid 1 into cinerubin.["'  The wild  type  is  known  for  it's  abililty  to  produce  aklavinone  12  and  aklavinone-I1 13." Thus, we  have demonstrated  for the first  time  that rela-  tively simple achiral unnatural  precursors can be converted  in a multistep biotransformation with high yield (56 YO) into  optically  active  anthracyclinones.  4-Demethoxy  analogues  of  daunorubicin  compounds  have  already  been  clinically  used and have proved to be more effective against tumors in  vitro  than  the natural compounds.[' 31 With  this  new  "hy-  brid"  synthetic  technique,  in  which  chemical  synthesis  is  combined with a multistep biotransformation,  it will be pos-  sible  to  use  other  mutants  to  produce  glycosidic  anthra-  c y ~ l i n o n e s . " ~ ~  Furthermore, the synthesis of the biosynthetic  intermediates  1 and 2 is designed  to enable isotopic labeling  and thus allow  the biosynthesis to be  investigated in  more  detail.

A total of 34 mg of 4-deoxyaklanonic acid 2 was added to  the cultures of the strain S727 in the feeding experiments (1 1  flasks each with 80 mL of culture medium). After an incuba-  tion  period of 24 h, the pH of the cultures  was adjusted to  8.5,  and  the  metabolites  were  extracted  with  chloroform/  methanol  (9: 1,  v/v).  Thin-layer  chromatography revealed  three  red  to  violet  minor  products and  two  yellow  major  products.  The polar compound  (3 mg)  exhibits the  typical  behavior  of  anthracyclinones hydroxylated  twice  in  ring A  (dehydration to yield fluorescent naphthacenediones).
